cago White Sox]] by [[Delmon Young]]<ref name=\"walk-off hits\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/tiny/dGhrJ|title=Team Batting Event Finder: From 1925 to 2018, All Teams, Hits, Walk-off, at TargetFld|work=Baseball Reference|accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Walk-Off Home Run\n|August 17, 2010 vs. Chicago White Sox by [[Jim Thome#Minnesota Twins (since 2010)|Jim Thome]]<ref name=\"walk-off hits\"/>\n|-\n\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Postseason Game\n|October 6, 2010 vs. [[2010 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|All-Star Game Hosted\n|July 15, 2014 \u2013 [[National League]] @ [[American League]]\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Soccer Match Hosted\n|June 25, 2016 \u2013 [[Minnesota United FC (2010\u201316)|Minnesota United FC]] vs [[Club Le\u00f3n]]\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Football Game Hosted\n|September 23, 2017 \u2013 [[University of St. Thomas (Minnesota)|St. Thomas Tommies]] vs [[Saint John's Johnnies football|St. John\u2019s Johnnies]]\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Walk-off Grand Slam\n|July 15, 2018 vs. [[2018 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]] by [[Brian Dozier]]<ref name=\"walk-off grand slam\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/tiny/3Avbz|title=Team Batting Event Finder: In the Postseason, From 1925 to 2018, All Teams, Home Runs, Walk-off, at TargetFld, With Runners on 123|work=Baseball Reference|accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Comparison to the Metrodome==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:right;\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Minnesota Twins}};|'''''Characteristic'''''\n! style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Target Field\n! style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Minnesota Twins}};|H.H.H. Metrodome\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Seats\n| 38,544* || 46,564**\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Lower Deck Seats\n| 19,000 || 21,621\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Private Suites\n| 54 || 115***\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Group Party Suites\n| 12 || 1\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Club Level Seats\n| 7,000 || \u2014\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Upper Deck Seats\n| 13,468 || 28,779\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Disabled Seating\n| 820 || 190\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Lower/Club Seats<br> between 1st and 3rd Base\n| <small>about</small> 12,037 || 6,679\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Outfield Seats\n| <small>about</small> 6,748 || 18,594\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Seats with Obstructed Views\n| < 200 || 1,392\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Main Concourse\n| {{convert|40|ft|m}},<br> open to field || {{convert|22|ft|m}},<br>closed to field\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Minnesota Twins}};|Total Restrooms\n| 34 || 16\n|}\n: *This is the official capacity.  However, Standing Room Only (SRO) tickets are available that can increase this capacity by approximately 2,500+.\n: **6,000 seats were covered by a curtain; these and others made the stadium expandable to 55,883 during baseball playoffs and certain games in the last homestand and one-game playoff in October 2009.\n: ***Controlled by the [[Minnesota Vikings]] football team.\n\nField dimensions are roughly comparable, with the left field area being a few feet closer to the plate, and the center field area being bounded by a 45\u00b0 facet instead of a quarter-circle.\n\nThe Twins' previous homes in the Twin Cities, [[Metropolitan Stadium]] and the Metrodome, were friendly to hitters. The team intended to build Target Field as a \"neutral\" park, favoring neither hitters nor pitchers. However, following the 2010 regular season, statistics seemed to show that the park played more to the favor of pitchers than hitters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/05/sports/baseball/05twins.html?src=un&feedurl=http%3A%2F%2Fjson8.nytimes.com%2Fpages%2Fsports%2Fbaseball%2Findex.jsonp|title=Power Still Off at Twins\u2019 New Home|last=Borzi|first=Pat|date=October 5, 2010|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 5, 2010}}</ref>  It became known as a \"pitcher's park\" in that it is difficult for batters to hit home runs and the pitcher has an advantage. Twins star [[Justin Morneau]] spoke for many of the players' concerns by calling \"right-center to left-center... ridiculous\" and that it is \"almost impossible for a right-handed hitter to [homer to the] opposite field and very difficult for lefties\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Justin Morneau Laments Target Fences|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=5796135|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=November 12, 2010|accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref>  Since 2010, further studies indicated both the Twins and their opponents fared much better in  other offensive categories in spite of the lack of home runs and runs scored. Target Field doesn't come off as being primarily a pitcher's park anymore.<ref name=\"Pitchers_Paradise\">{{cite web |last1=Bryzgornia |first1=Andrew |title=Target Field: A Pitcher's Paradise No More |url=https://www.twinkietown.com/2014/12/17/7406221/is-target-field-a-pitchers-park-or-hitters-park |accessdate=8 October 2019 |website=Twinkie Town |publisher=SBNation |date=17 December 2014 |quote=Target Field is often cited as a safe haven for pitcher's, but that narrative is no longer true.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball|United States}}\n* [[List of NCAA Division I baseball venues]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://minnesota.twins.mlb.com/min/ballpark/ Stadium site on twinsbaseball.com]\n* [http://www.ballparkauthority.com Minnesota Ballpark Authority] official website\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051029220113/http://www.house.leg.state.mn.us/bills/billnum.asp?billnumber=HF2480&session_number=0&ls_year=84&year=2005 The Twins Stadium Bill] MN State Legislature HF2480, SF2297\n* [http://www.leg.state.mn.us/lrl/issues/baseball.asp Minnesota Legislative Reference Library: Baseball Stadiums]\n* [http://www.ballparkmagic.com BallparkMagic (Target Field Construction Blog)]\n* [http://www.mlb.com/min/ballpark/new_banter.jsp?content=qa Ballpark FAQ]\n* [http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=5796135 sports.espn.go.com]\n* [http://wheresmyseat.net/target-field-minneapolis-mn/ Target Field Seating Chart]\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{s-sta|et}}}}\n{{succession box\n | title = Home of the<br>[[Minnesota Twins]]\n | years = 2010 \u2013 present\n | before = [[Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome]]\n | after = Current\n}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Host of the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game]] \n|years=[[2014 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2014]]\n|before=[[Citi Field]]\n|after=[[Great American Ball Park]]\n}}\n}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Host of the [[NHL Winter Classic]] \n|years= 2021\n|before=[[Cotton Bowl (stadium)|Cotton Bowl]]\n|after= TBA\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Minnesota Twins}}\n{{MLB Ballparks}}\n{{Big Ten Conference baseball venue navbox}}\n{{Minneapolis skyscrapers}}\n{{Music venues of Minnesota}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball venues in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:College baseball venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design basic silver certified buildings]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Golden Gophers baseball]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Twins stadiums]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball venues]]\n[[Category:Rugby union stadiums in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 2010]]\n[[Category:Sports venues i